      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "He felt shame and took a different decision\nHe would swap places with the boy.\nThinking to himself\nI wonder if they will be happy now"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "bloom",
      "title": "Bloom",
      "uuid": "c8ff77d05c50404d86ab61420900f371",
      "x": 14603.716012582936,
      "y": 6507.57447704269,
      "width": 464.34050376959,
      "height": 324.54013540088704,
      "z_value": -9.941000000000033,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "scatter_mode": "sprinkle",
      "particle_count": 5000,
      "seed": 42,
      "density_falloff": "center",
      "stiffness": 0.62,
      "speed": 0.86,
      "distance": 386.0,
      "depth_front": false
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "Again he felt Shame",
      "uuid": "eb872eb651c04202b76d954a88ab00fe",
      "x": 8711.835147387555,
      "y": 7405.734151284834,
      "width": 290.19825644594766,
      "height": 216.0,
      "z_value": -9.943000000000032,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Later another group of men passed by\nPointed angrily at them saying look at this!\nIs this what you call caring these days?\nSitting on a Donkey\nLeaving a poor child running behind\n\nAgain he felt ashamed\nAnd told the boy to ride on the Donkey with him."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "about",
      "title": "No, its not a lot of interesting caves to explore\nits just a gigantic hole in the ground \nwhere your building used to be\n\nwith pictures of famous caves\nyou know, a cave museum",
      "uuid": "499dd5a1b4254cd891ce7b9747142c55",
      "x": 13686.434820033735,
      "y": 5941.2701724089,
      "width": 524.9779881250367,
      "height": 194.90864799011354,
      "z_value": -9.942000000000032,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": false,
      "label": "No, its not a lot of interesting caves to explore\nits just a gigantic hole in the ground \nwhere your building used to be\n\nwith pictures of famous caves\nyou know, a cave museum",
      "depth_front": false,
      "node_tint": "#2a3a2f"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "Market",
      "uuid": "62da15ce78774d46a2c5147797599e0d",
      "x": 8706.69999829951,
      "y": 6762.128798916687,
      "width": 329.95503634692204,
      "height": 152.0,
      "z_value": -9.94600000000003,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "He went to market one day and brought along his son\nTogether they purchased a Donkey.\nOn the way back he let the boy ride the Donkey\nAnd took a decision to walk alongside himself."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "Omnious",
      "uuid": "1fded24b84584ca3bec6de3b27e09324",
      "x": 15304.543667843664,
      "y": 7160.3634826960315,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 312.0,
      "z_value": -9.934000000000037,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "This is Basalt\nSay hello to Basalt everyone\nBasalt is special\n\nIt\u00b4s a bit stiff when it gets here\nSo we need to be kind to it\n\nIt gets totally crushed\n\nHow do we measure\nAggression versus compassion\n\nTime, becoming the gardeners ally\nWithin our tapestry of shared success"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "Look!",
      "uuid": "a65cecf92e974bdf9c3112043bce2b75",
      "x": 8760.61906372397,
      "y": 6969.2464788011175,
      "width": 304.5752017114978,
      "height": 152.0,
      "z_value": -9.94500000000003,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "During this walk home they met some men\nWho began prying into their affairs.\nStarted shouting look! look! look at that little boy!\nLeaving a poor old man tired walking behind"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "Bloom",
      "uuid": "d0312e7684b04ec6b3f21d30f6a1db9b",
      "x": 13031.907963457097,
      "y": 5168.103213772524,
      "width": 594.716934060388,
      "height": 702.4828568256082,
      "z_value": -9.918000000000045,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "The full chain from empty tab to \"Intricate\" showing up:\n1. Get a code signing certificate\nSelf-signed (free, for learning the process): New-SelfSignedCertificate in PowerShell, won't be trusted by other machines\nPaid CA (for real distribution): DigiCert, Sectigo, GlobalSign \u2014 roughly $200-400/year for standard, $400+ for EV (Extended Validation, required for SmartScreen reputation on day one)\nAzure Trusted Signing (newer, cheaper): ~$10/month, Microsoft acts as the CA, handles the HSM requirement that EV certs now mandate\n2. Sign with signtool.exe\nsigntool sign /fd SHA256 /tr http://timestamp.digicert.com /td SHA256 /f certificate.pfx /p password about_node.ico\n\nThat populates the Embedded Signatures tab. The /tr timestamp means the signature stays valid after the cert expires.\n3. What gets signed in the MSI pipeline\nSign each .exe and .dll first (pythonw.exe wrapper, any .pyd like the Rust logger)\nThe .ico files CAN be signed but typically aren't \u2014 they travel inside the signed MSI/EXE\nSign the .msi itself last\nThe MSI signature is what Windows, SmartScreen, and UAC actually check\n4. The realistic path for Intricate\nThe icons don't need individual signatures \u2014 they're embedded resources inside the signed installer\nWhat matters is: signed .msi \u2192 signed .exe entry point \u2192 SmartScreen trusts it\nThe ICO Digital Signatures tab is interesting but it's the MSI and EXE signatures that gate the user experience\nSo the short answer: that tab will say \"Intricate\" when you run signtool sign against the file with a certificate whose Subject CN is \"Intricate\". But in practice, you'd sign the MSI and the frozen EXE, not the individual icons.\nWorth doing a dry run with a self-signed cert to see the full flow before spending money on a real one. Want me to generate one and sign an icon as a proof of concept?"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "Thank You",
      "uuid": "8db0fd7a21804c70acae62a4f8f745b3",
      "x": 14774.812948196417,
      "y": 5186.239816359066,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 344.0,
      "z_value": -9.930000000000039,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "First of all thank you.  \n\nBut mostly because it is important for us to remember \nThat in this world a human being saw some chickens \n\nAnd thought, hey! \nWhy is our world so amazing \nAnd their world so dirty and dark. \n\nAnd then went ahead and invented virtual reality goggles\nThat fit snuggly on the heads of chickens \nSo they run around on paradisic fields all day \nIn absolute joy and bliss as advertised on TV."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "about",
      "title": "Note",
      "uuid": "9bf2d76b5743440fb8dc6789cf91dbbb",
      "x": 15765.375418807304,
      "y": 11010.05493411143,
      "width": 867.0,
      "height": 52.0,
      "z_value": -9.913000000000048,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": false,
      "label": "source drifted \u2014 cache no longer matches\nIs this what you call caring these days.png",
      "depth_front": false,
      "node_tint": ""
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "null",
      "title": "Null",
      "uuid": "e850f569c2354d3d944f683f48696c0e",
      "x": 14519.880791317377,
      "y": 6974.814048732567,
      "width": 190.42648273156442,
      "height": 115.6928071961549,
      "z_value": -9.933000000000037,
      "ports_visible": true,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "depth_front": false
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "Onward",
      "uuid": "a010802157494390a8fa293f16c7be69",
      "x": 12424.186977788944,
      "y": 5799.3488827568635,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 488.0,
      "z_value": -9.917000000000046,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Good edge case \u2014 yes, exactly. If you're distributing a standalone icon pack through the Microsoft Store, there's no EXE to hide behind. The store package itself (MSIX/APPX) would be signed, but if you also want individual ICO files to carry provenance after extraction \u2014 so someone right-clicks about_node.ico on their desktop and sees \"Intricate\" in that Digital Signatures tab \u2014 then you'd sign each ICO individually.\nThat's the scenario where ICO signing actually matters: the file IS the product, not a resource bundled inside one.\nThe store submission itself uses your MSIX signing certificate, but that signature lives on the package container. Once the user extracts or copies an ICO out of the install folder, the package signature doesn't follow it. The embedded Authenticode signature on the ICO itself is what persists.\nSo the pipeline for an icon bundle would be:\nGenerate all ICOs (your Pillow recipe)\nsigntool sign each ICO individually\nPackage into MSIX, sign the MSIX\nSubmit to store\nBoth layers \u2014 ICO-level and package-level \u2014 carrying your certificate."
    },
